Integral representation of the natural logarithm.
The natural logarithm of "t" equals the integral of 1/"x" "dx" from 1 to "t":
In other words, ln("t") equals the area between the "x" axis and the graph of the function 1/"x", ranging from to (figure at the right). This is a consequence of the fundamental theorem of calculus and the fact that derivative of ln("x") is 1/"x". The right hand side of this equation can serve as a definition of the natural logarithm. Product and power logarithm formulas can be derived from this definition. For example, the product formula is deduced as:
